          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"week_number\":1,\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weekly_target_km\":40,\"is_deload_week\":false,\"days\":[{\"day_of_week\":0,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"notes\":\"Easy long run at 5:50–6:27/km. Keep effort conversational throughout. Cap at 75 min. Today is about time on feet and building your aerobic engine — not pace.\"},{\"day_of_week\":1,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Full rest day. Recovery is where adaptation happens — this is a productive day, not a lost one.\"},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"Easy run at 5:50–6:27/km for 8–9 km. Focus on relaxed form and controlled breathing. A great day to check in with how your legs feel after Sunday.\"},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"slot_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"notes\":\"Low-impact cross-training: cycling, swimming, or yoga. 30–45 min. This keeps aerobic stimulus going while giving your legs a break — especially smart given your IT band history.\"},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"notes\":\"Tempo run: 10 min easy warm-up, then 20 min at 4:50/km threshold pace, 10 min easy cool-down. This is your weekly quality session — threshold work is the single biggest lever for half-marathon performance.\"},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest or very light walk. Let Thursday's quality work absorb. Your body is making adaptations right now.\"},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"Easy run at 5:50–6:27/km for 8–9 km. Keep it light and enjoyable. A good day to focus on cadence and relaxed shoulders.\"}],\"week_summary\":\"Welcome to Week 1, Lee — and a great starting point. Your VDOT of 42.0 from your February 10K gives us a solid, data-grounded foundation to work from. Your 1:45 half-marathon goal is genuinely achievable: it requires roughly a 4:59/km race pace, which sits just above your current marathon pace estimate. That gap is closeable over 16 weeks with smart, consistent training.\\n\\nThis first week mirrors your recent best weekly volume (40 km) to ease you in without shock-loading your system. The structure is built around three principles: aerobic base on easy days, one quality threshold session per week during this Base phase, and a long run that grows gradually each week. The cross-training day on Wednesday is intentional — given your IT band history, keeping one non-impact aerobic day per week is a smart insurance policy. The two rest days give your connective tissue time to adapt alongside your cardiovascular system. What questions do you have about this first week, and how does the overall structure feel to you?\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
